					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-9902272#post-4241807</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-9902272/scp-4511#post-4241807</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 07 May 2019 23:59:43 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Anyar</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5274479</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I did like this SCP and gave it +1. The (at first subtle) compulsion of researchers made me wonder &quot;why is the Foundation just doing what 4511 says?&quot; It also explains the cult, the casually mentioned deaths and even shoving a kid into the fire (I'm still on the fence on whether that's too brutal for the sake of being brutal, as others have mentioned).</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Some&nbsp;suggestions</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>Of course, it's not the first time an SCP has fats and other bodily liquids in abundance. So I found this section of the dialogue a bit weird:</p> <blockquote> <p>ε-1 gestures to the catwalk floor, and the shallow puddle of yellow liquid covering it.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p>ε-4: Fuck me, I think I'm going to vomit…</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p>ε-3: God, that's… who the fuck does that?</p> </blockquote> <p>As far as I can tell, this highly trained Foundation task force is apparently appalled and chilled to the core by a moderate dollop of pee. Even if they'd already seen the flesh (which they haven't yet), they're way too disturbed given their training and roles, especially since they reacted much more mildly to the fat-clogged fuse box.</p> <p>The only explanation I can think of is that 4511 has mind-affecting properties beyond compulsion, which I don't believe is hinted at.</p> <p>Now, after they see the fleshy growth in the ceiling&#8230;</p> <blockquote> <p>ε-1: (quietly) Keep moving. One of you guys, make sure you're looking at it.</p> </blockquote> <p>This also seems to contradict what I'd expect from a skilled task force leader. He's just saying &quot;someone look at it&quot;, instead of assigning one person to do it (e.g. &quot;Three, keep an eye on the ceiling&quot;). This doesn't break the story, but it's something that stood out to me.</p> <p>As a side note, I made a few small edits, mainly changing verbs to treat &quot;team&quot; as a singular collective noun (&quot;team is&quot; instead of &quot;team are&quot;). Some verbs already treated &quot;team&quot; as singular but it was inconsistent; needless to say, feel free to revert if plural is preferred.</p> </div> </div> </div> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
